comment_data.body: Are you use mac m1 chip. I have same problem

> Are you use mac m1 chip. I have same problem

Yeah. M1 16gb RAM.
I think issue may be from dart sdk, flutter build in dart sdk still use for intel, if you change build in by another dart sdk native m1, it will faster. but can not run project

@LucasTran380381 Can you show the latency analytics difference between Intel and Native Dark SDK?

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/36441457/137627004-f5c1b8c4-01c7-420d-9551-81a2591a5b8c.png)

when use native sdk without build in flutter I can not run project. but, I can clearly feel it faster than intel sdk. But I found that if use code dart, just dart file with class not widget, It show completion very fast
@zanderso @jmagman @christopherfujino - is the Dart SDK built and vended into the Flutter SDK build as x86 or Apple Silicon?
@devoncarew Is this a dart-lang/sdk issue?
I think if flutter use dart sdk native for m1. It make better

> @devoncarew Is this a dart-lang/sdk issue?

If the perf issue is that the Dart SDK inside the Flutter SDK isn't built for apple silicon, than the issue should live in the flutter repo. cc @a-siva who has more knowledge of the dart sdk built for apple silicon (and whether the current dart sdk does something like have a fat binary). Steve, there should be an existing issue in the flutter repo for shipping an apple silicon native dart sdk; if you do de-dup this into that issue it would be worth adding info about the impact there (2x completion times).
/move dart-lang/sdk
@stevemessick hello Steve, I have change dart sdk by native sdk in flutter, but it can not run vm.

> If the perf issue is that the Dart SDK inside the Flutter SDK isn't built for apple silicon, than the issue should live in the flutter repo. cc @a-siva who has more knowledge of the dart sdk built for apple silicon (and whether the current dart sdk does something like have a fat binary). Steve, there should be an existing issue in the flutter repo for shipping an apple silicon native dart sdk; if you do de-dup this into that issue it would be worth adding info about the impact there (2x completion times).

No, the current Dart SDK does not build a fat binary, we have one SDK for macOS/X64 and one for macOS/Arm64.

> @stevemessick hello Steve, I have change dart sdk by native sdk in flutter, but it can not run vm.

@LucasTran380381 can you elaborate a bit on what you mean by change dart sdk by native sdk in flutter and it can not run vm ?

> @zanderso @jmagman @christopherfujino - is the Dart SDK built and vended into the Flutter SDK build as x86 or Apple Silicon?

We currently only distribute the x86 Dart SDK with Flutter.
@christopherfujino yeah, you are right. I don't have option dart for arm

@a-siva I download dart sdk for native arm, then replace folder in flutter folder. When it run

Launching lib/main.dart on sdk gphone64 arm64 in debug mode...
lib/main.dart:1
Snapshot not compatible with the current VM configuration: the snapshot requires 'release no-code_comments
no-dwarf_stack_traces_mode lazy_async_stacks lazy_dispatchers 
use_bare_instructions no-dedup_instructions
no-"asserts" "use_field_guards" "use_osr" x64-sysv no-null-safety' but the VM has 'release no-code_comments no-
dwarf_stack_traces_mode lazy_async_stacks 
lazy_dispatchers use_bare_instructions no-dedup_instructions no-"asserts" "use_field_guards" "use_osr" arm64-sysv no-null-safety'
2
the Dart compiler exited unexpectedly.

I've checked the difference between native M1 and x86 implementation of the analysis and the difference is huge. With native implementation, almost all code completions fall under the 100ms baseline. If I remember correctly @scheglov mentioned that there will be work for the analysis in Q4.
cc @jacob314 to raise awareness wrt the impact on code completion times
Any news on this? I've also noticed when the project grows the whole analyzer and IntelliSense becomes painfully slow which lags the whole IDE.

> @a-siva I download dart sdk for native arm, then replace folder in flutter folder. When it run
> 
> Launching lib/main.dart on sdk gphone64 arm64 in debug mode... lib/main.dart:1 Snapshot not compatible with the current VM configuration: the snapshot requires 'release no-code_comments no-dwarf_stack_traces_mode lazy_async_stacks lazy_dispatchers use_bare_instructions no-dedup_instructions no-"asserts" "use_field_guards" "use_osr" x64-sysv no-null-safety' but the VM has 'release no-code_comments no- dwarf_stack_traces_mode lazy_async_stacks lazy_dispatchers use_bare_instructions no-dedup_instructions no-"asserts" "use_field_guards" "use_osr" arm64-sysv no-null-safety' 2 the Dart compiler exited unexpectedly.

This error with mismatched snapshot versions is correct. When you manually replace the Dart sdk in the flutter folder you would bring in a different version of the SDK than the one which is used in the flutter engine and hence the version mismatch. Please see https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/84453 for the engine specific issue and https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/60118 for the overall list of tasks still pending.
@a-siva is there any way to run flutter with dart sdk for arm
Imagine my disappointment when I setup my new m1 max pro laptop.  Android Studio is painful to use right now.

> Imagine my disappointment when I setup my new m1 max pro laptop. Android Studio is painful to use right now.

Use arm version! I use android studio in my mac mini m1 and itâ€™s insane fast

> > Imagine my disappointment when I setup my new m1 max pro laptop. Android Studio is painful to use right now.
> 
> Use arm version! I use android studio in my mac mini m1 and itâ€™s insane fast

oh really??  Well, I'm using the Apple Silicon Android Studio install.  Are you talking about replacing the dart folder like discussed earlier?  Sounds like there are issues with that.
https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/86926 should help with this.

Apple Silicon Dart SDK is available since [flutter-2.11-candidate.7](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/tree/flutter-2.11-candidate.7)

Any update?
